        <link rel="schema.DC" href="https://purl.org/DC/elements/1.0/" /><meta name="citation_journal_title" content="RadioGraphics" /><meta name="dc.Title" content="Uncommon Congenital and Acquired Aortic Diseases: Role of Multidetector CT Angiography1" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Eric T.  Kimura-Hayama" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Gabriela  Meléndez" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Ana L.  Mendizábal" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Aloha  Meave-González" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Greby Fernando B.  Zambrana" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Celia P.  Corona-Villalobos" /><meta name="dc.Description" content="Uncommon diseases of the aorta—including those that are congenital in origin and acquired disorders—are described, with emphasis on their findings at multidetector CT." /><meta name="Description" content="Uncommon diseases of the aorta—including those that are congenital in origin and acquired disorders—are described, with emphasis on their findings at multidetector CT." /><meta name="dc.Description" content="State-of-the-art multidetector computed tomographic (CT) technology has replaced invasive angiography for evaluation of patients suspected to have aortic disease. Although most aortic disease is as..." /><meta name="Description" content="State-of-the-art multidetector computed tomographic (CT) technology has replaced invasive angiography for evaluation of patients suspected to have aortic disease. Although most aortic disease is as..." /><meta name="dc.Publisher" content=" Radiological Society of North America" /><meta name="dc.Date" scheme="WTN8601" content="2010-01-01" /><meta name="dc.Type" content="research-article" /><meta name="dc.Format" content="text/HTML" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="doi" content="10.1148/rg.301095061" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="publisher-id" content="0300079" /><meta name="dc.Source" content="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.301095061" /><meta name="dc.Language" content="en" /><meta nam