</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">State-of-the-art multidetector computed tomographic (CT) technology has replaced invasive angiography for evaluation of patients suspected to have aortic disease. Although most aortic disease is associated with atherosclerosis (ie, aneurysms and dissection), the spectrum of aortic disease is vast and includes various congenital and acquired entities. Radiologists should also be familiar with uncommon aortic diseases, which are divided into those that are congenital in origin and acquired disorders, and with their findings at multidetector CT. The first group includes patent ductus arteriosus, aortic hypoplasia, aortic coarctation, interrupted aortic arch, aortopulmonary window, common arterial trunk, supravalvular aortic stenosis, and vascular rings. The acquired disorders include aortic dissection due to extension of a coronary artery dissection, Marfan syndrome, large-vessel vasculitis such as Takayasu arteritis, and mycotic aneurysms. Finally, specific conditions associated with therapeutic maneuvers—such as recoarctation, stent-graft rupture, and endoleaks—can also be assessed with multidetector CT. Multidetector CT is an alternative tool helpful in establishing the primary diagnosis, defining anatomic landmarks and their relationships, and identifying associated cardiovascular anomalies. It is also an adjunct in the evaluation of complications during follow-up.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.301095061">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.301095061">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061c01x.jpeg" height="963" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f1-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Embryonic aortic arches. Rathke diagram shows the six pairs of embryonic aortic arches and the seventh intersegmental arteries (<a href="#b4-0300079" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b4-0300079">4</a>). The ventral and dorsal aortas are connected by the six arches (dotted circles), which experience several changes until final configuration by 8 weeks of fetal life. Dotted lines represent segments that normally involute. The text boxes on the right and left explain the normal and abnormal embryonic development of the aortic arches. Solid circles represent the aortic arches that persist in each case. <i>AA</i> = aortic arch, <i>L</i> = left, <i>R</i> = right.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f1-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10a-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061c10a.jpeg" height="1233" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f10a-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Type B IAA in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered image shows aortic interruption with an aberrant right subclavian artery <i>(RSA)</i> and significant dilatation of the pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i>. The ascending aorta (large arrow) continues as the right (large arrowhead) and left (small arrow) common carotid arteries; a PDA (small arrowhead) gives origin to the descending aorta. <i>LSA</i> = left subclavian artery. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis cardiac multi-planar reformatted CT image shows a VSD (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f10a-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10b-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g10b.jpeg" height="1467" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10b-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Type B IAA in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered image shows aortic interruption with an aberrant right subclavian artery <i>(RSA)</i> and significant dilatation of the pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i>. The ascending aorta (large arrow) continues as the right (large arrowhead) and left (small arrow) common carotid arteries; a PDA (small arrowhead) gives origin to the descending aorta. <i>LSA</i> = left subclavian artery. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis cardiac multi-planar reformatted CT image shows a VSD (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f10b-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11a-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g11a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1469" aria-labelledby="f11a-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Type II aortopulmonary window in a 44-year-old man who underwent CT angiography because of pulmonary artery hypertension. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered <b>(b)</b> CT images show a communication (*) between the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i> just above the valvular plane. <b>(c)</b> CT image shows a right aortic arch.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f11a-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11b-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061c11b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1117" aria-labelledby="f11b-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Type II aortopulmonary window in a 44-year-old man who underwent CT angiography because of pulmonary artery hypertension. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered <b>(b)</b> CT images show a communication (*) between the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i> just above the valvular plane. <b>(c)</b> CT image shows a right aortic arch.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f11b-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11c-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g11c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1466" aria-labelledby="f11c-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> Type II aortopulmonary window in a 44-year-old man who underwent CT angiography because of pulmonary artery hypertension. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered <b>(b)</b> CT images show a communication (*) between the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i> just above the valvular plane. <b>(c)</b> CT image shows a right aortic arch.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f11c-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061l12x.jpeg" height="516" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f12-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Mori classification of aortopulmonary window (<a href="#b29-0300079" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b29-0300079">29</a>). Type I or proximal communication occurs near the semilunar valves. Type II or distal communication involves the pulmonary bifurcation at the level of the right pulmonary artery. In type III, there is a wide communication between the aorta and pulmonary artery owing to total absence of the aortopulmonary septum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f12-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061l13x.jpeg" height="405" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f13-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Classification of truncus arteriosus according to Collett and Edwards (<a href="#b32-0300079" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b32-0300079">32</a>). The Collett and Edwards classification is the most commonly used. In type I, the pulmonary artery trunk arises from the proximal portion of the truncus arteriosus. In types II and III, there is no pulmonary artery trunk and the pulmonary branches arise from the posterior and lateral mid-segments of the truncus, respectively. Finally, in type IV, the pulmonary circulation is dependent on major aortopulmonary collateral arteries.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f13-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f14a-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g14a.jpeg" height="1751" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f14a-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Main difference between aortopulmonary window and truncus arteriosus. <b>(a)</b> Valvular plane multiplanar reformatted CT image of aortopulmonary window shows separate valves for the aortic root <i>(Ao)</i> and pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i>. <b>(b)</b> Valvular plane multiplanar reformatted CT image of truncus arteriosus <i>(TA)</i> shows only one truncal valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f14a-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f14b-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g14b.jpeg" height="1775" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f14b-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Main difference between aortopulmonary window and truncus arteriosus. <b>(a)</b> Valvular plane multiplanar reformatted CT image of aortopulmonary window shows separate valves for the aortic root <i>(Ao)</i> and pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i>. <b>(b)</b> Valvular plane multiplanar reformatted CT image of truncus arteriosus <i>(TA)</i> shows only one truncal valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f14b-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f15a-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061c15a.jpeg" height="1203" width="1126" aria-labelledby="f15a-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Type IV truncus arteriosus in a 27-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal volume-rendered image with partial cutoff of the trunk shows a major aortopulmonary collateral artery (arrow) arising from the left subclavian artery. <b>(b)</b> Anterior volume-rendered image shows multiple major aortopulmonary collateral arteries arising from the descending aorta (arrowheads) and aortic arch (arrows). These collateral vessels perfuse both lungs. (According to the new classification, this type of truncus arteriosus is now considered a variant of pulmonary atresia.) <b>(c)</b> Coronal volume-rendered image, obtained in a 20-year-old man with type I truncus arteriosus, shows the truncus arteriosus <i>(TA)</i> arising from the heart. Truncal bifurcation into the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and main pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i> is seen a few centimeters above the valvular plane. The truncal valvular plane CT image (inset) shows that the truncus arteriosus has a bicuspid valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f15a-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f15b-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061c15b.jpeg" height="1088" width="1088" aria-labelledby="f15b-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Type IV truncus arteriosus in a 27-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal volume-rendered image with partial cutoff of the trunk shows a major aortopulmonary collateral artery (arrow) arising from the left subclavian artery. <b>(b)</b> Anterior volume-rendered image shows multiple major aortopulmonary collateral arteries arising from the descending aorta (arrowheads) and aortic arch (arrows). These collateral vessels perfuse both lungs. (According to the new classification, this type of truncus arteriosus is now considered a variant of pulmonary atresia.) <b>(c)</b> Coronal volume-rendered image, obtained in a 20-year-old man with type I truncus arteriosus, shows the truncus arteriosus <i>(TA)</i> arising from the heart. Truncal bifurcation into the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and main pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i> is seen a few centimeters above the valvular plane. The truncal valvular plane CT image (inset) shows that the truncus arteriosus has a bicuspid valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f15b-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f15c-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061c15c.jpeg" height="1280" width="1068" aria-labelledby="f15c-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span> Type IV truncus arteriosus in a 27-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal volume-rendered image with partial cutoff of the trunk shows a major aortopulmonary collateral artery (arrow) arising from the left subclavian artery. <b>(b)</b> Anterior volume-rendered image shows multiple major aortopulmonary collateral arteries arising from the descending aorta (arrowheads) and aortic arch (arrows). These collateral vessels perfuse both lungs. (According to the new classification, this type of truncus arteriosus is now considered a variant of pulmonary atresia.) <b>(c)</b> Coronal volume-rendered image, obtained in a 20-year-old man with type I truncus arteriosus, shows the truncus arteriosus <i>(TA)</i> arising from the heart. Truncal bifurcation into the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and main pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i> is seen a few centimeters above the valvular plane. The truncal valvular plane CT image (inset) shows that the truncus arteriosus has a bicuspid valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f15c-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16a-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g16a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1764" aria-labelledby="f16a-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> SVAS in a 19-year-old woman with a family history of sudden death in two brothers. At physical examination, subtle radial pulses were noted. Coronal multiplanar reformatted image <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered image <b>(b)</b> show an area of stenosis (arrow) of the ascending aorta. The stenosis starts at the sinotubular junction and extends along the entire ascending aorta and proximal arch. Note the concentric hypertrophy of the left ventricular myocardial wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f16a-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16b-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061c16b.jpeg" height="1152" width="1141" aria-labelledby="f16b-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> SVAS in a 19-year-old woman with a family history of sudden death in two brothers. At physical examination, subtle radial pulses were noted. Coronal multiplanar reformatted image <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered image <b>(b)</b> show an area of stenosis (arrow) of the ascending aorta. The stenosis starts at the sinotubular junction and extends along the entire ascending aorta and proximal arch. Note the concentric hypertrophy of the left ventricular myocardial wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f16b-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f17-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g17x.jpeg" height="1097" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f17-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Diagrams of double aortic arch (left) and right aortic arch (right). The origins of the supraaortic branches may vary from those shown (<a href="#b4-0300079" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b4-0300079">4</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f17-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18a-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g18a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1797" aria-labelledby="f18a-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Coronary dissection extending into the aortic root in a 55-year-old man with atherosclerotic coronary artery disease who underwent coronary angiography. During the intervention, a dissection of the right coronary artery (RCA) with extension into the aortic root was produced. A stent was placed in the proximal RCA to limit further aortic dissection. Coronary CT angiography was performed 1 hour after the procedure. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal multiplanar reformatted <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images show a flap of aortic dissection with entrapment of the high-attenuation contrast material used during catheterization (*), which comes directly from the dissected RCA. Note the coronary dissection flap (arrow in <b>b</b>) immediately distal to the stent. <b>(c–e)</b> Multiplanar reformatted <b>(c, d)</b> and curved-planar reformatted <b>(e)</b> images from follow-up CT performed 2 days later show no progression of the aortic dissection (arrows in <b>c</b>) as well as occlusion of the RCA (arrow in <b>e</b>). Note that the proximal portion of the stent (arrowhead in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>) projects into the aortic lumen and that the RCA fills through collateral vessels distal to the occlusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f18a-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18b-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g18b.jpeg" height="1795" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f18b-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Coronary dissection extending into the aortic root in a 55-year-old man with atherosclerotic coronary artery disease who underwent coronary angiography. During the intervention, a dissection of the right coronary artery (RCA) with extension into the aortic root was produced. A stent was placed in the proximal RCA to limit further aortic dissection. Coronary CT angiography was performed 1 hour after the procedure. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal multiplanar reformatted <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images show a flap of aortic dissection with entrapment of the high-attenuation contrast material used during catheterization (*), which comes directly from the dissected RCA. Note the coronary dissection flap (arrow in <b>b</b>) immediately distal to the stent. <b>(c–e)</b> Multiplanar reformatted <b>(c, d)</b> and curved-planar reformatted <b>(e)</b> images from follow-up CT performed 2 days later show no progression of the aortic dissection (arrows in <b>c</b>) as well as occlusion of the RCA (arrow in <b>e</b>). Note that the proximal portion of the stent (arrowhead in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>) projects into the aortic lumen and that the RCA fills through collateral vessels distal to the occlusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f18b-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18c-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g18c.jpeg" height="1747" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f18c-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span> Coronary dissection extending into the aortic root in a 55-year-old man with atherosclerotic coronary artery disease who underwent coronary angiography. During the intervention, a dissection of the right coronary artery (RCA) with extension into the aortic root was produced. A stent was placed in the proximal RCA to limit further aortic dissection. Coronary CT angiography was performed 1 hour after the procedure. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal multiplanar reformatted <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images show a flap of aortic dissection with entrapment of the high-attenuation contrast material used during catheterization (*), which comes directly from the dissected RCA. Note the coronary dissection flap (arrow in <b>b</b>) immediately distal to the stent. <b>(c–e)</b> Multiplanar reformatted <b>(c, d)</b> and curved-planar reformatted <b>(e)</b> images from follow-up CT performed 2 days later show no progression of the aortic dissection (arrows in <b>c</b>) as well as occlusion of the RCA (arrow in <b>e</b>). Note that the proximal portion of the stent (arrowhead in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>) projects into the aortic lumen and that the RCA fills through collateral vessels distal to the occlusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f18c-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18d-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g18d.jpeg" height="1765" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f18d-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18d</span> Coronary dissection extending into the aortic root in a 55-year-old man with atherosclerotic coronary artery disease who underwent coronary angiography. During the intervention, a dissection of the right coronary artery (RCA) with extension into the aortic root was produced. A stent was placed in the proximal RCA to limit further aortic dissection. Coronary CT angiography was performed 1 hour after the procedure. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal multiplanar reformatted <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images show a flap of aortic dissection with entrapment of the high-attenuation contrast material used during catheterization (*), which comes directly from the dissected RCA. Note the coronary dissection flap (arrow in <b>b</b>) immediately distal to the stent. <b>(c–e)</b> Multiplanar reformatted <b>(c, d)</b> and curved-planar reformatted <b>(e)</b> images from follow-up CT performed 2 days later show no progression of the aortic dissection (arrows in <b>c</b>) as well as occlusion of the RCA (arrow in <b>e</b>). Note that the proximal portion of the stent (arrowhead in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>) projects into the aortic lumen and that the RCA fills through collateral vessels distal to the occlusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f18d-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18e-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g18e.jpeg" height="1800" width="777" aria-labelledby="f18e-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18e</span> Coronary dissection extending into the aortic root in a 55-year-old man with atherosclerotic coronary artery disease who underwent coronary angiography. During the intervention, a dissection of the right coronary artery (RCA) with extension into the aortic root was produced. A stent was placed in the proximal RCA to limit further aortic dissection. Coronary CT angiography was performed 1 hour after the procedure. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal multiplanar reformatted <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images show a flap of aortic dissection with entrapment of the high-attenuation contrast material used during catheterization (*), which comes directly from the dissected RCA. Note the coronary dissection flap (arrow in <b>b</b>) immediately distal to the stent. <b>(c–e)</b> Multiplanar reformatted <b>(c, d)</b> and curved-planar reformatted <b>(e)</b> images from follow-up CT performed 2 days later show no progression of the aortic dissection (arrows in <b>c</b>) as well as occlusion of the RCA (arrow in <b>e</b>). Note that the proximal portion of the stent (arrowhead in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>) projects into the aortic lumen and that the RCA fills through collateral vessels distal to the occlusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f18e-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g19x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1787" aria-labelledby="f19-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span> Annuloaortic ectasia in a 32-year-old man with Marfan syndrome. Radiography showed mediastinal enlargement. Image from CT angiography shows an aneurysm of the aortic root with effacement of the sinotubular junction and aortic regurgitation (not shown). Note the typical “tulip bulb” configuration of the aortic root.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f19-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g02x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1761" aria-labelledby="f2-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Diagram of the thoracic aorta and its segments. The aortic root <i>(<a href="#b1-0300079" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b1-0300079">1</a>)</i> is composed of the valvular plane <i>(1a)</i>, Valsalva sinuses <i>(1b)</i>, and sinotubular junction <i>(1c)</i>. The normal diameters of the proximal arch <i>(3A)</i>, distal arch <i>(3B)</i>, and isthmus <i>(<a href="#b4-0300079" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b4-0300079">4</a>)</i> should be at least 60%, 50%, and 40% of the diameter of the ascending aorta <i>(<a href="#b2-0300079" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b2-0300079">2</a>)</i> (<a href="#b5-0300079" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b5-0300079">5</a>). In an infant, the segments of the aortic arch (<i>3A</i>, <i>3B</i>, and <i>4</i>) have a maximal length of 5 mm. Some authors also consider the diameter proximal to the brachiocephalic trunk <i>(BT)</i>. Arrows indicate areas where aortic measurements are usually taken. <i>5</i> = descending aorta, <i>LCC</i> = left common carotid artery, <i>LSA</i> = left subclavian artery, <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f2-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f20-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061c20x.jpeg" height="1280" width="1002" aria-labelledby="f20-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span> Abdominal aortic occlusion in an asymptomatic 30-year-old woman with type IV Takayasu arteritis. Volume-rendered image shows occlusion of the infrarenal aorta (arrowheads) with distal reconstitution through a prominent Riolan arch (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f20-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f21-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061c21x.jpeg" height="1280" width="994" aria-labelledby="f21-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span> Multiple mycotic aneurysms in a 62-year-old man who presented to the emergency department with fever and chest pain. Left lateral volume-rendered image shows multiple saccular and lobulated aneurysms (arrows) involving the entire descending aorta. Three blood cultures were all positive for <i>Streptococcus</i> species. The patient received intravenous penicillin therapy with an adequate response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f21-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f22a-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g22a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1583" aria-labelledby="f22a-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span> Type II endoleaks from an aortic stent in a 41-year-old man with Marfan syndrome who underwent Bentall–De Bono surgery (placement of an aortic root graft with aortic valve replacement) and placement of a Talent stent-graft (Medtronic, Minneapolis, Minn) in the aortic arch and descending aorta. Reformatted (candy cane view) <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> images from CT angiography show the expected difference in diameter of the ascending aorta between the junction of the surgical graft (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) and the native aorta. (White line in <b>a</b> indicates the level at which <b>b</b> was obtained.) There is also incomplete apposition of the endograft to the aortic wall secondary to its angulation, along with type II endoleaks in the proximal and distal arch (small arrows in <b>a</b>, arrow in <b>b</b>). The endoleaks were secondary to retrograde flow through the left subclavian artery (not shown). There is also distal aortic dissection (large arrow in <b>a</b>). * = contrast material in a false lumen due to the type II endoleaks.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f22a-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f22b-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g22b.jpeg" height="1546" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f22b-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span> Type II endoleaks from an aortic stent in a 41-year-old man with Marfan syndrome who underwent Bentall–De Bono surgery (placement of an aortic root graft with aortic valve replacement) and placement of a Talent stent-graft (Medtronic, Minneapolis, Minn) in the aortic arch and descending aorta. Reformatted (candy cane view) <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> images from CT angiography show the expected difference in diameter of the ascending aorta between the junction of the surgical graft (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) and the native aorta. (White line in <b>a</b> indicates the level at which <b>b</b> was obtained.) There is also incomplete apposition of the endograft to the aortic wall secondary to its angulation, along with type II endoleaks in the proximal and distal arch (small arrows in <b>a</b>, arrow in <b>b</b>). The endoleaks were secondary to retrograde flow through the left subclavian artery (not shown). There is also distal aortic dissection (large arrow in <b>a</b>). * = contrast material in a false lumen due to the type II endoleaks.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f22b-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f23-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g23x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1725" aria-labelledby="f23-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span> Aortic stent thrombosis in a 23-year-old man with a history of aortic coarctation, which was treated with percutaneous intervention at the age of 19 years. The patient experienced thoracic pain, and systemic artery hypertension developed. Maximum intensity projection image (candy cane view) from CT angiography shows partial thrombosis of the stent with a significant in-stent stenosis (arrow). There was prominent collateral flow through intercostal arteries (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f23-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f24-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061c24x.jpeg" height="1280" width="1200" aria-labelledby="f24-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span> Aortic stent rupture in a 20-year-old man with a history of aortic coarctation, which was treated percutaneously with an aortic stent. The patient was asymptomatic. Volume-rendered image from follow-up CT angiography shows a multifragmented rupture of the aortic stent (inset).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f24-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f25-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g25x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1727" aria-labelledby="f25-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span> Stenosis of a carotid-subclavian graft in a 25-year-old man with a history of aortic coarctation, which was treated percutaneously with an aortic stent. The distal portion of the stent partially occluded the origin of the left subclavian artery. A carotid-subclavian graft was surgically placed. Maximum intensity projection image (candy cane view) from follow-up CT angiography shows a significant stenosis (short arrow) in the proximal segment of the surgical graft (arrowheads). Long arrow = aortic stent, <i>LCC</i> = left common carotid artery, <i>LS</i> = left subclavian artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f25-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3a-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061c03a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1089" aria-labelledby="f3a-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Patent ductus arteriosus (PDA). <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered image obtained in a 25-year-old woman shows a PDA (arrow), which is type A or conical according to the classification of Krichenko et al (<a href="#b7-0300079" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b7-0300079">7</a>). Note the enlargement of the pulmonary artery (*). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis view obtained in another patient with a PDA (not shown) shows signs of pulmonary artery hypertension with right cardiac involvement: right ventricular dilatation (*), flat configuration of the septum (arrows), right ventricular hypertrophy, and a D-shaped left ventricle (dotted line).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f3a-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3b-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g03b.jpeg" height="1692" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3b-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Patent ductus arteriosus (PDA). <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered image obtained in a 25-year-old woman shows a PDA (arrow), which is type A or conical according to the classification of Krichenko et al (<a href="#b7-0300079" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b7-0300079">7</a>). Note the enlargement of the pulmonary artery (*). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis view obtained in another patient with a PDA (not shown) shows signs of pulmonary artery hypertension with right cardiac involvement: right ventricular dilatation (*), flat configuration of the septum (arrows), right ventricular hypertrophy, and a D-shaped left ventricle (dotted line).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f3b-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061l04x.jpeg" height="660" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f4-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Aortic hypoplasia and coarctation. Left diagram shows isthmic aortic hypoplasia. The diameter of the isthmus (small arrow) is less than 40% of that of the reference segment (ie, the ascending aorta) (large arrow). Nevertheless, hypoplasia may be seen in any segment of the arch, and even diffuse involvement can be identified. Aortic hypoplasia is frequently associated with aortic coarctation. Right diagram shows aortic coarctation (arrowhead), which is focal narrowing of the thoracic descending aorta in a juxtaductal location. Aortic coarctation is commonly associated with dilatation of the left subclavian artery (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f4-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g05x.jpeg" height="1356" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> Aortic isthmic hypoplasia and coarctation in a 1-month-old boy. Maximum intensity projection reformatted CT image (“candy cane” view) shows abnormal tapering of the aortic arch (arrowhead) and an area of coarctation (large arrow). The diameter of the isthmus is less than 40% of that of the ascending aorta. The proximal intercostal arteries are prominent (small arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f5-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6a-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061c06a.jpeg" height="1219" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f6a-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Juxtaductal aortic coarctation in a 28-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered image from CT angiography shows a focal narrowing at the aortic arch (arrow), a prominent left internal mammary artery (arrowheads), and prominent intercostal arteries. <b>(b)</b> Volume-rendered image shows the collateral circulation, with prominent internal mammary arteries (arrowheads) and descending scapular arteries (arrows). These vessels reconstitute the aorta distally through the inferior epigastric and intercostal arteries, respectively.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f6a-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6b-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061c06b.jpeg" height="1217" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f6b-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Juxtaductal aortic coarctation in a 28-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered image from CT angiography shows a focal narrowing at the aortic arch (arrow), a prominent left internal mammary artery (arrowheads), and prominent intercostal arteries. <b>(b)</b> Volume-rendered image shows the collateral circulation, with prominent internal mammary arteries (arrowheads) and descending scapular arteries (arrows). These vessels reconstitute the aorta distally through the inferior epigastric and intercostal arteries, respectively.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f6b-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g07x.jpeg" height="1795" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> BAV in a patient with aortic coarctation. Multiplanar reformatted image from ECG-gated CT shows a noncalcified BAV. BAV is commonly associated with aortic coarctation, being present in up to 42% of cases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f7-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061g08x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1731" aria-labelledby="f8-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Aortic pseudocoarctation in a 65-year-old man. Multiplanar reformatted CT image (candy cane view) shows a calcified plaque (arrowhead) and aortic pseudocoarctation (arrow). Note the elongation of the aorta, which is more evident in the descending thoracic aorta and might be misinterpreted as a coarctation. In this case, the elongated aorta may be secondary to the incorporation of the ventral aorta extending into the third segment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f8-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9-0300079" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.301095061/asset/images/g095061l09x.jpeg" height="407" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f9-0300079" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Celoria and Patton classification of IAA (<a href="#b22-0300079" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b22-0300079">22</a>). Type A is defined as an interruption distal to the left subclavian artery <i>(LSA)</i>. In type B, the absent segment is between the left common carotid artery <i>(LCC)</i> and left subclavian artery. Type C is defined as an interruption distal to the innominate artery <i>(IA)</i>. Note that the descending thoracic aorta reconstitutes from the pulmonary artery <i>(PA)</i> through a ductus arteriosus. <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.301095061&amp;id=f9-0300079">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="b1-0300079" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Lee CH, Goo JM, Ye HY, et al.Radiation dose modulation techniques in the multidetector CT era: from basics to practice. <em>RadioGraphics</em> 2008; 28:1451–1459.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.285075075">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18794318/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Radiation+dose+modulation+techniques+in+the+multidetector+CT+era%3A+from+basics+to+practice&amp;author=CH+Lee&amp;author=JM+Goo&amp;author=HY+Ye&amp;publication_year=2008&amp;journal=RadioGraphics&amp;pages=1451-1459&amp;doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075075&amp;pmid=18794318">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="b2-0300079" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Hausleiter J, Meyer T, Hadamitzky M, et al.Radiation dose estimates from cardiac multislice computed tomography in daily practice: impact of different scanning protocols on effective dose estimates. <em>Circulation</em> 2006;113:1305–1310.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.105.602490">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16520411/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://s